50|$|There {{were many}} links between royalty and {{the cult of}} saints, with many saints having been born to royal {{families}} and many churches having been established by royalty. In the Kingdom of Kent, saints' cults were typically located at abbeys which were also royal vills and therefore centres of royal administration. Royalty could use their affiliation to such cults in order <b>to</b> <b>claim</b> <b>legitimacy</b> against competitors <b>to</b> the throne. A dynasty may have had accrued prestige for having a saint in its family. Promoting a particular cult may have aided a royal family in claiming political dominance over an area, particularly if it was recently conquered.|$|R
